english:
  title: Preface to the Posthumous Works of Master Bokjae
  author: An Sung-seon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Literature exists to give voice to our inner nature and to reveal what dwells within the heart. Thus harmony must first take root in the depths before brilliance can blossom outward. The robust and elegant words of the masters spring from the vital essence itself—proof that true writing cannot be forged or false.

    My maternal uncle, the Lord of Seowon, Master Bokjae Jeong Gong, appeared in the twilight of Goryeo. Heaven blessed him with keen intellect and nimble mind; his learning was vast and encompassing. Early he passed the examinations with distinction, rising swiftly through the ranks of office. He became a pillar of our Great Founder, earning merit that touched the very foundations of state and altar. All the nation's proclamations, decrees, and diplomatic correspondence—whether tribute or alliance—flowed from his brush. His words and virtue became the standard of his age. Yet in the year of eulhae, he departed on an embassy and never returned. Thus did a mind meant to order the world, a talent both grand and luminous, remain forever unfulfilled. Alas, what a loss.

    His second son, the General Hyoochung, came to me with a request: "My father's manuscripts are to be published. Would you, elder brother, write a preface?" Along with his words, he placed a volume in my hands. Though my own writing is meager, I could not refuse on principle. So I lit incense, sat in stillness, and spent days turning through these pages. What I found was prose refined yet never frivolous, plain yet never coarse—clarity emerging from subtle depths, vastness unfolding from profound sources. The affection for sovereign and concern for nation flow abundantly through every line, surpassing what any mere wordsmith or poet could hope to achieve.

    My ancestors, Master Seolgok and Master Wonjae, left behind collections widely known to the world. My uncle inherited their household teachings and faithfully preserved their methods. His own poetry and prose continue this legacy. Though our land has never lacked literary scholars, I have not heard of three generations—father, son, and grandson—each leaving behind collected works in succession. The General's earnest determination to honor his forebears and transmit their memory to all eternity deserves to be recorded. This is why I could not refuse to write.
  footnotes:
    - 'Eulhae year (乙亥): This refers to 1395, when Jeong Gong was sent as an envoy and did not return, likely due to political circumstances during the founding of the Joseon Dynasty.'
    - 'Seolgok and Wonjae: These refer to An Hyang''s ancestors, literati whose collections were well-known, establishing a family tradition of literary excellence.'
    - The dedication to preserving and transmitting literary legacy across generations reflects the Confucian values central to early Joseon intellectual culture.
